				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Oh. Well, good we cleared that up. So we have the correct timing and aspect ratio, we have all the video levels, we have the NTSC encoder/decoder for standard NTSC as well as for several modern Sony TVs (they should be in the source I sent you)...
<br />
<br />So what prevents us from having "perfect" NES video as God intended? 
<br />1. Different filter. Again, real TVs likely don't use a two-way Gaussian blur. I dabbled with a real low-pass filter in the spatial domain, but didn't get it to work right. Also, low-pass filters create these "ringing" artifacts which I have never seen on a real TV...
<br />
<br />2. Non-standard, Japanese 80s' chroma decoder. We'd need a Japanese 80s' TV, identify the electronics responsible for chroma decoding and measure the output given a certain input. Got one? Know how to get one? <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

