				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">You need to use a filter that doesn't have any ringing. I think a Bessel fits the bill. Did you look at the <a href="http://www.jwz.org/xscreensaver/" class="postlink">analogtv module in the XScreenSaver package</a>? I still haven't tried the code, but it has what I consider the "next level" features. One thing it does is work at many times the NTSC rate. I kind of want to do that for the NES PPU; generate a signal at the ~21.5 MHz rate the PPU phase counter runs at, then resample that. This way you generate the actual NES video waveform with no use of sin(). I just calculated and realized that we're already running at 14.32 MHz, so bumping up to 21.5 MHz is only a 50% increase.
<br />
<br />I'm still unclear on the horizontal pixel correspondence. Color burst is at 3.58 MHz, and the I and Q components are 90 degress out of phase, so it takes a sample rate 4x that, 14.32 MHz. NES pixels run at 5.37 MHz, so each pixel lasts for 2.66667 samples. Then you're saying that you take this 752-sample signal, convert it to RGB at the same sample rate, then interpolate down to 640 or something close to that? I think I get it now. What was throwing me off is that I thought that you output the 720 raw, because I thought, why else would you expand to 720 if it wasn't supposed to be that wide? But that expansion is in the raw signal domain, necessary to achieve a sufficient sampling rate.
<br />
<br />We really need some quality control. I know I've contributed to it, but we'll have all these emulators based to varying degrees on the latest findings in this area, with people thinking NTSC NES emulation has been reached (it hasn't) and saying we failed (even though we're not done). That's one reason posting RGB palettes is premature (or even inappropriate, since NTSC NES emulation is not about choosing the correct palette).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

