				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">You had color subcarrier at 1.79 MHz. That's just wrong, as TVs only understand 3.58 MHz. The counter used to generate the 12 phases seems to be a 21.5 MHz double-pumped counter, which increments at 43 MHz.</div><br /><br />Yeah, this morning I was going over the color phases and got really stumped about how the hell it gets 12 phases. So apparently the phase generator is clocked on the positive <em>and</em> negative edges of the clock. I'm doing more measurements right now to get the phase aspects cleaned up.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Quietust wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The entire GOAL of my emulator is to be as accurate as possible, and this is one part of it. I do not, however, plan to emulate an NTSC (or PAL) television within my emulator, mainly because it would then require a Beowulf cluster (imagine it!) to run at maximum speed.</div><br /><br />I have some new ideas for an all-integer implementation that should run comfortably on a mid-level machine. What I really want to do is run the output to a high-speed D/A convertor, resulting in a real composite video output from the PC that exactly matches the NES output. But that'd be a hell of a lot of data to generate and output over the bus (43 MB/sec, assuming an 8-bit D/A).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">guest wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The current NTSC screenshots I've seen, while impressive, tend to have a bit more artifacting than I remember actually seeing. They look like a really *bad* TV set. I used to play the NES [...] it was nowhere near as blurred as some of the NTSC emulated screenshots. Am I misremembering?</div>
<br />
<br />You're correct; the NTSC emulation code I've posted (and which Nestopia is based on) is poor, mostly due to the lossy optimizations I made to bring it from 2 frames per second to 50. I want to do a lot better and allow adjustment of the amount of artifacts.</div>

