				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Guest wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The current NTSC screenshots I've seen, while impressive, tend to have a bit more artifacting than I remember actually seeing.</div>Screenshots will only show one single field. The NES' artifacting works in such a way that the artifacts will (appear to) cancel each other out over several fields. That's why a still screenshot will always appear to have more artifacts than the real thing. Just look at the video-captured screenshots on MobyGames.<br />You need to compare a real NES to an emulator running NTSC artifacting (running at full speed with perfect vertical synchronization), not to a screenshot. Of course, the emulator should implement the artifacting correctly, which Nestopia 1.25 doesn't.<br /><br />That's also the reason why I think getting the video levels right is more important than the artifacting. With the proper video levels, the user can choose a virtual TV's hue/saturation/decoder coefficients and thus create his own, subjectively perfect RGB palette to match his taste or home TV. That goal has already been achieved! (Though I think there are some rounding errors in blargg's values. I'll check again later using the original waveform he posted. Also, I think it would be proper to convert those values to voltage levels, or even better, IRE levels; since the voltages for Sync and Blanking are defined, it should be possible to get the voltages even from blargg's normalized waveform.)<br /><br />Artifacting again will only work properly if your emulator has perfect "vsync", an option unavailable to many people because many monitors don't run at 60 Hz, at least not in their default settings, and I also consider it negligible to the average user, although certainly exciting to explore and emulate. (From that point of view, I also think we shouldn't be satisfied with those measured level values, but instead try to find out how exactly they come about, with reference to the "resistor ladder" described in the NES' patent.)<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">What I really want to do is run the output to a high-speed D/A convertor, resulting in a real composite video output from the PC that exactly matches the NES output.</div>I've got a feeling that after resampling/filtering, you'll end up with the same result as my original algorithm (with the correct levels, of course).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

